<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-267-680  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 267 680.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 15 1989 v23 n20 p62(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PCs bloom on plant floor. (microcomputers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stevens, Larry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Personal Computers are becoming common on the manufacturing floor,where a large range of functions are benefiting from the lowercosts and increased flexibility and efficiency that PCs offer.andO;Automation Research Corp Pres Andy Chatha predicts that over100,000 PCs are sold for manufacturing use each year and that thecurrent PC installed base is over a million.andP;  Catha also predictsthat this number will increase as faster PCs replace existing IBMPC XT and AT computers.andP;  PC-based manufacturing, especially whenconnected in efficient local area networks (LAN), rival the powerof minicomputers and mainframes.andP;  In addition, the cost ofPC-based manufacturing LANs is often 50 percent the price ofminicomputer systems.andP;  Software availability remains a concern formanufacturing users, although Chatha says ample off-the-shelfPC-based manufacturing packages are available.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersApplicationsPerformance-Cost RelationshipLocal Area NetworksFactory management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>